@section Interfaces
@anchor{Interfaces}

There are four (4) @dfn{STREAMS} service primitive interfaces normally provided
by the X.25 implementations.  These are:

@table @cite
@item Data Link Provider Interface (DLPI)

The Data Link Provider Interface (DLPI) is an UNIX International standard
interface maintained by the OpenGroup that is in Revision 2.0.0 with corrigenda.
For X.25, DLPI normallly provide direct access to the X.25 LAPB protocol or
ISO/IEC 8802 LAPB.

It is specified by ``@cite{Open Group CAE Specification: Data Link Provider
Interface (DLPI) Sepcification, Revision 2.0.0, Draft 2, August 20, 1991,
(Parsippany, New Jersey), UNIX International, Inc., UNIX International
Press.},'' available from @uref{http://www.openss7.org/docs/dlpi.pdf,The OpenSS7
Project}.@footnote{@file{dlpi.pdf} is distributed with this package.}

@item Network Layer Interface (NLI)

The Network Layer Interface (NLI) is an non-standard interface developed by
Spider, that provides access to the remnants of their X.25, XOL, XOT
implemetnations.  This interface is prevelant in @cite{Solaris}, @cite{HP-UX},
@cite{IRIX}, and other systems.

@item Network Provider Interface (NPI)

The Network Provider Interface (NPI) is a UNIX International standard interface
maintained by the OpenGroup that is in Revision 2.0.0 with corrigenda.  For
X.25, NPI normally provides OSI CONS over X.25, but some implementations use it
for direct access to X.25 (@cite{AIX} does this).

It is specified by ``@cite{Open Group CAE Specification: Network Provider
Interface (NPI) Specification, Revision 2.0.0, Draft 2, August 17, 1992,
(Parsippany, New Jersey), UNIX International, Inc., UNIX International Press.},''
available from @url{http://www.openss7.org/docs/npi.pdf,The OpenSS7
Project}.@footnote{@file{npi.pdf} is distributed with this package.}

@item X/Open X.25 Interface (XX25)

The X/Open X.25 Interface (XX25) is an standard interface developed by X/Open
and maintained by the OpenGroup.

It is specified by ``@cite{Open Group CAE Specification: X.25 Programming Interface
using XTI (XX25), Document No: C411, November 1995, (Berkshire, UK), X/Open,
Open Group Publication. [ISBN: 1-85912-136-5]}'' available from
@url{http://www.opengroup.org/onlinepubs/, The Open Group}.

@end table

@section Aspects

There are several aspects of porting from the various environments to
@cite{Linux Fast-STREAMS} that can be categorized roughly by the functional
interface to which the aspect corresponds.  These aspects are:

@itemize
@item @cite{Addressing} --
The Addressing aspect is the aspect of associating an address with the local
endpoint and addresses associated with remote endpoints.

@item @cite{Modes} --
The Modes aspect is the aspect of major operating modes of enpoints.

@item @cite{Primitives} --
The Primitives aspect is the aspect of implementing service primitives accross
the service primitive interface.

@item @cite{Input-Output Controls} --
The Input-Output control aspec is the aspect of providing
impelementation-specific input-output control for the control of major aspect
modes, replacement for primtives, or management and administration of the
interface.

@item @cite{Drivers and Modules} --
The Drivers and Modules aspect is the naming, enumeration, and linkage of driver
and modules into protocol stacks.

@item @cite{Libraries and Utilities} --
The Libraries and Utilities aspect is the aspect of C-language programs and
shared object libraries the provide access to the interfaces or permit in the
control of modes, protocol actions, management and adminstration, or protocl
stakc construction and maintenance.

@item @cite{Management} --
The Management aspect is, of course, the aspect of management of the interface
and protocol stack implemetnation using standard SNMP MIBs or CMIP GDMOs.

@end itemize

The aspects can be applied to each of four (4) interfaces offered to X.25 LAPB
and PLP users, described under @ref{Interfaces}.

The sections that following provide an overview of each of these aspects.  Also,
each specific porting section has sub-sections that detail each of these aspects
of a specific porting scenario.

